          "id": "economics-101-l02-c1",
          "title": "The Demand Curve",
          "content": "The demand curve is an important tool in economics that visually represents how the price of a good influences the quantity that consumers are willing to purchase, while keeping all other factors constant. This curve typically slopes downward, which illustrates a key principle known as the law of demand: when the price of a good rises, the quantity demanded by consumers tends to fall. Conversely, when prices decrease, consumers are likely to buy more of that good.\nSeveral factors can cause the entire demand curve to shift, meaning that at every price level, the quantity demanded changes. These factors include changes in consumer income, which can affect purchasing power; shifts in consumer preferences, which can make certain goods more or less desirable; and the prices of related goods, which include substitutes (goods that can replace each other) and complements (goods that are often used together). Additionally, expectations about future prices and changes in population size can also influence demand. By understanding these factors, we can better predict how demand for a good might change in different situations, helping businesses and policymakers make informed decisions.\nContext recap: The demand curve is an important tool in economics that visually represents how the price of a good influences the quantity that consumers are willing to purchase, while keeping all other factors constant. This curve typically slopes downward, which illustrates a key principle known as the law of demand: when the price of a good rises, the quantity demanded by consumers tends to fall. Conversely, when prices decrease, consumers are likely to buy more of that good. Several factors can cause the entire demand curve to shift, meaning that at every price level, the quantity demanded changes.\nWhy this matters: The Demand Curve helps learners in Business connect ideas from Microeconomics Foundations to decisions they make during practice and assessment. Highlight tradeoffs, assumptions, and verification."
